---

## 🔐 What is Passport.js?

**Passport.js** is an **authentication middleware for Node.js**.
It helps you implement **login, signup, and session-based authentication** easily.

---

## 🚀 Passport.js – Getting Started (Basic Steps)

### 1️⃣ Install required packages

npm install passport-local-mongoose

## 🧠 What Passport does for you

- Password hashing
- Login verification
- Session management
- User authentication

---

## ✍️ One-line Viva Answer

> **Passport.js is an authentication middleware for Node.js used to implement secure login and session-based authentication.**

### 🔹 `passport.initialize()`

> Initializes Passport in the Express application so it can handle authentication requests.

📌 Without this, Passport **will not work**.

### 🔹 `passport.session()`

> Enables Passport to use **sessions** to remember logged-in users across multiple requests.

📌 This keeps the user **logged in** after authentication.

### 🔹 `passport.use(new LocalStrategy(User.authenticate()))`

> Defines the **local authentication strategy** using username and password, and tells Passport how to verify user credentials using the User model.

📌 It checks whether the **entered username and password are correct**.

## 🧠 One-line combined explanation (excellent for viva)

> `passport.initialize()` starts Passport, `passport.session()` manages login sessions, and `passport.use()` defines how users are authenticated using a local strategy.

## 🔁 In your project (WanderBNB)

- **Users & Hosts** login using Passport
- Authentication → login check
- Authorization → role-based access (user / host)

passport.serializeUser(User.serializeUser());

Stores the user’s ID in the session after successful login.

📌 This decides what data is saved in the session (not the full user).

🔹 passport.deserializeUser(User.deserializeUser());

Retrieves the full user details from the database using the stored user ID on every request.

📌 This makes req.user available.

🧠 Simple flow (easy to remember)

User logs in
serializeUser → saves user ID in session
On next request
deserializeUser → fetches user from DB

✍️ One-line Viva Answer

serializeUser saves the user ID in the session, and deserializeUser retrieves the user details from the database for each request.
